{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}} {{Infobox aircraft occurrence |name = 1946 KLM Douglas DC-3 Amsterdam accident |occurrence_type = Accident |image = Douglas C-47A PH-TBP KLM ed Ringway 20.05.47 edited-2.jpg |image_size = 250px |alt = |caption = A KLM DC-3 in 1947 |date = {{start date|1946|11|14}} |summary = Poor weather, [[Controlled flight into terrain|CFIT]] |site = [[Amsterdam Schiphol Airport]], Netherlands |coordinates = |aircraft_type = [[Douglas C-47 Skytrain|Douglas C-47A Skytrain]] |aircraft_name = |operator = [[KLM]] |tail_number = PH-TBW |origin = London, United Kingdom |stopover = |stopover0 = |stopover1 = |stopover2 = |stopover3 = |last_stopover = |destination = [[Amsterdam Schiphol Airport]], Netherlands |passengers = 21 |crew = 5 |injuries = |fatalities = 26 |survivors = 0 }}
The '''1946 KLM Douglas DC-3 Amsterdam accident''' was the crash of a [[KLM|KLM Royal Dutch Airlines]] flight from London to Amsterdam on 14 November 1946. The accident occurred as the [[Douglas DC-3]] was attempting to land at Amsterdam's airport in poor weather. All 26 passengers and crew on board were killed in the accident.
==Accident== The DC-3 (actually an ex-military [[Douglas C-47 Skytrain|C-47 Skytrain]] converted for civil use) was on a scheduled flight from London, England to [[Amsterdam]] in the Netherlands.<ref name="TBW"/> The crew was cleared to land the aircraft at Schiphol Airport in poor weather. The first attempt to land failed and the crew had to perform a [[go-around]]. The second approach to land also failed. On the third approach to land the aircraft made a sudden turn to the left, apparently trying to line up with the runway.<ref name="TBW"/> During this turn the Douglas DC-3 struck the ground and crashed. The aircraft caught fire on impact, killing all 21 passengers and five crew on board.<ref name="TBW"/>
At the time it happened, the 1946 KLM Amsterdam accident was the worst aviation accident in the history of the Netherlands.<ref name="TBW">[http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19461114-0 Aircraft accident Douglas C-47A-90-DL PH-TBW Amsterdam-Schiphol Airport]</ref> Eight days earlier another KLM DC-3 operating on the same route in the opposite direction, crashed on approach to London's [[Croydon Airport]] in poor weather. There were no fatalities in the London crash but the aircraft was written off.<ref>[http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19461106-0 Aircraft accident Douglas C-47A-90-DL PH-TBO near Shere, 6 November 1946] retrieved 8 July 2012</ref>
