'''Drought Cycle'''<ref>{{Cite book|title = Encyclopedia of Latin American Literature|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=bFdc24rnt_IC|publisher = Taylor & Francis|date = 1997-01-01|isbn = 9781884964183|first = Verity|last = Smith}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title = Concise Encyclopedia of Latin American Literature|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=VJmnAgAAQBAJ|publisher = Routledge|date = 2014-01-14|isbn = 9781135960261|first = Verity|last = Smith}}</ref> is the name given to the "drought [[novels]] cycle," a Brazilian literary era that had as main theme the life in the Brazilian [[Sertão|backlands]].

It began with the publication of [[O sertanejo]] of [[José de Alencar]] (1876), and lasted until the first decade of the twentieth century. The main characters of the drought cycle literature are [[bandits]], [[human migration|migrants]] and [[blesseds]]. In the cycle stand the [[Ceará]] writers.<ref>{{Cite book|title = The Cambridge History of Latin American Literature|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=97NoYRx96ZAC|publisher = Cambridge University Press|date = 1996-09-19|isbn = 9780521410359|first = Roberto Gonzalez|last = Echevarría}}</ref>
: "[[Os Sertões|Os sertões]] was a landmark, work of sociology, literature and war story, written by [[Euclides da Cunha]] with obvious admiration for the country people, understanding their struggles against nature and protest against the contempt with which handles the federal government."
[[Gilberto Freyre]] was influenced by this literary tendency. Other relevant authors are [[Rachel de Queiroz|Raquel de Queirós]], [[José Lins do Rego]], [[Jorge Amado]], [[Graciliano Ramos]], [[Antônio Callado]], until [[João Guimarães Rosa|Guimarães Rosa]].

