'''Magazine paper''' are [[paper]] grades generally used in [[printing]] of [[magazine]]s.
==Manufacture== {{Main|Paper machine}} Magazine papers are made on paper machines from [[pulp (paper)|pulp]]. The pulp may be recycled, mechanical or chemical depending on the magazine quality. [[Publisher]]s select the type of paper that not only meets their customers' requirements, but also works well in their machinery.
==Paper grades== Different paper grades are used in magazines: * Machine finished specialties (MFS) is a special [[newsprint]] grade that is heavier, bulkier and brighter. * [[Supercalendered]] papers are often used in [[rotogravure]]. These are uncoated and based on mechanical pulp. * [[Coated paper|Coated mechanical paper]] are classified depending on the coating weight. Normally higher coating weight gives higher paper quality. * [[Machine finished coated paper]]s are high gloss papers based on mechanical pulp. * [[Offset paper]] is an uncoated paper based on chemical pulp suitable for [[offset printing]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Parker|first=Amely|title=Club Flyer Paper List|url=http://www.printingvip.com/products/clubflyers|publisher=VIP Printing Marketing |accessdate=21 June 2013 }}</ref> * Standard [[coated fine paper]]s are often used for offset printing. * Woodfree Papers made only from [[cellulose]], usually containing less than 10% mechanical content. Coated woodfree or uncoated woodfree. Also Known as free sheet (USA).
